part 14 আনান এক পলক নিধীর দিকে তাকিয়ে পাশকাটিয়ে চলে জেতে নিলে।বুশরা নিধীকে চিমটি কেটে বুজালো করে।  কিছু বলতে।নিধী হঠাৎ “আহ” বলে উঠলো। আনান পিছন ফিরে তাকিয়ে নিধী উদ্দেশ্যে বল্লো.. -- কি হয়েছে। ব্যাথা পেয়েছো?  এই বলেই আনান নিধীর হাত ধরে নিলো।নিধী তো থ মেরে গেলো। কারন আসে পাশে অনেকেই তাদের দিকে তাকিয়ে আছে। তাই নিধী তার থেকে হাত ছারিয়ে নিলো এক ঝটকায়। আনান নিধীর ঝারা দেয়াতে বেশ বিরক্ত হলো কিন্তু মুখে কিছু বল্লো না। চলে যেতে নিলে নিধী পিছন ডাকদিলো.. -- আনান। আনান তার ডাকে থেমে গেলো।একটু আগের বিরক্তি আর তার মুখে নেই। এখন যেনো কেমন এর মুখে ভাব দেখে বুঝা জাবে না সে কি ভাবছে। সে পিছন ঘুরে নিধীর দিকে তাকলো.. -হু বলো। নিধী আমতা আমতা করে বল্লো.. -বুশরা আমাদের বাসায় যাবে। আর ও চায় তুমিও আমাদের সাথে চলো। বুশরা নিধীর মুখের পানে তাকিয়ে চোখ বড় করে রাগ দেখালো। এটা কেমন কথা সে চায়?  আমাদোর সাথে চলো এটা না বলে মেয়ে উলটা পালটা বলে।আনান একবার বুশরার দিলে তাকায় তার পর নিধীর দিকে তাকিয়ে বলে..  -- তুমি কি চাও?  নিধীর চোখ বড় বড় হয়ে যায়। সে ঢোক গিলে তার পর বলে..  -- আমিও চাই। আফটার অল তুমি আমাদের ফ্রেন্ড।  আনান সব সময় এর মতো গম্ভীর গলায় বল্লো.. -- হু চলো। নিধী আর বুশরা তো অবাক কারন এই ছেলে রাজি হয়ে গেলো এত সহজে। নিধী একটু অসস্থি বোধ করলেও বুশরা বেশ খুশি।আনান এখন ও নিধীর দিকে তাকিয়ে আছে.. -- কি ভাবো চলো?! নিধী হুসে ফিরলো। -- হু চলো।  বলেই তারা কলেজ গেইটের দিকে হাটতে লাগলো। আনান আর বুশরা নিধীর দুই পাশে দুজন।কেউ কোনো কথা বলছে না। কলেজ গেট এর সামনে আসতেই হঠাৎ রিভান এর চোখে পরলো।সে বাকা চোখে তাকিয়ে আছে তাদের দিকে। নিধীর একবার তার দিকে চোখ গেলো কিন্তু কিছু বল্লো না, বা বলার কিছু নেই। তারা রিভান কে পাশ কাটিয়ে চলে গেলো। কিন্তু রিভান সেই একই ভাবে তাদের জাওয়ার পানে তাকিয়ে আছে। বুশরা হাটতে হাটতে নিধীকে বল্লো.. -- নিধী তোকে রিভান স্যার কেনো ডেকেছিলো রে। নিধী ওর দিকে তাকিয়ে মুখ বাকিয়ে বল্লো.. -- জানি না। সামনে বসিয়ে রাখছে।  বুশরা অবাক হলো।  -- কিহ।এত সময় তুই শুধু বসে ছিলি ওনার সামনে।  -- হু  বুশরা এবার একটা দুষ্টু হাসি দিলো..  -- সত্যি করে বলতো কি চলছে তলে তলে? হু হু নিধী বিরক্ত হলো.. -- কিছু না।আমি নিজেও বিরক্ত হয়েছি খুব। বুশরা আবার ও দুষ্টু হাসি দিলো.. -- আমার মনে হয় উনি তোকে লাইক করে। শোন জদি প্রপোজ করে একসেপ্ট করে দিস। তোদের মানাবে। (আনান এর দিকে তাকিয়ে) কি আনান ঠিক বল্লাম না? আনান এতক্ষণ ওদের কথা শুনছিলো।প্রথমে তেমন গুরুত্ব না না নিলেও বুশরার এমন কথা সোনার পর তার চোখ একটু রাঙা হয়ে উঠলো। মুখটা ঠান্ডা, কিন্তু চোখে আগুন। -- না, মানাবে না। সরাসরি, গম্ভীর গলায় বলেই আনান সামনে হাঁটতে শুরু করলো। নিধী আর বুশরা দু’জনেই থমকে গেলো। নিধী তো একেবারে হা করে তাকিয়ে রইলো ওর দিকে। বুশরাও একটু চুপ করে গেলো কিছু সময়ের জন্য।নিধী আর বুশরা আনান এর পিছন ছুটলো।নিধী আনান এর সামনে গেলো নিধী হালকা গলায় বললো, -- এটা কী হলো হঠাৎ? তুমি রেগে গেলে নাকি?  আনান কিছু বললো না, শুধু ধীরে ধীরে বললো, -- রাগ বললে ভুল হবে... এইটুকু বোঝার মতো সময় তো তোমার হয়েছে নিধী। তুমি বোঝো না বললে সেটা মিথ্যে হবে। বলে ও সামনের দিকে চলে গেলো। নিধী হতবাক। সে কিছু বলতে গিয়েও চুপ করে গেলো। বুশরা এবার আস্তে করে বললো, -- নিধী, আনান কিন্তু তোকে খুব সিরিয়াসলি নেয় রে। তুই বুঝিস না? নিধী কিছু বললো না। মাথা নিচু করে হাঁটতে থাকলো। হাওয়া যেনো ভারী হয়ে গেলো চারপাশে। একটা চুপচাপ দুপুরে, তিনটা ছায়া মিশে গেলো রোদের রাস্তায়। ....................... তারা তিনজন বাড়ি পৌছালো। বুশরা তাড়াহুড়ো করে কলিং বেল বাজালো। কিছু সময় পর কেউ দরজা খুলে দিলো। বুশরা সামনে থাকাতে লোকটা আর বুশরা মুখো মুখি হলো। বুশরা নিহান কে দেখে একটু অপ্রস্তুত হলো।একটু মনে হয় লজ্জা পেলো।নিধী ওকে দারিয়ে থাকতে দেখে বল্লো.. -- এই মেয়ে ভেতরে যা। বাহিরেই থাকবি নাকি। বুশরার হুস ফিরলো। -- হু হু যাচ্ছি তো।  বুশরা নিহান এর দিকে একটু আর চোখে তাকালো নিহান তার দিকেই তাকিয়ে আছে। মুখে হালকা হাসি। বুশরা সামনে এগোলো। পিছনে নিধী আনান কে বল্লো.. -- চলো ভিতরে ( নিহান কে দেখিয়ে) এটা আমার বড় ভাইয়া।  আনান তার দিকে তাকলো। তার পর নিহান এর দিকে। তার পর ভিতরে প্রবেশ করলো।নিহান হাত বারিয়ে বল্লো। -- হেলো নিহান আনান তার দিকে তাকিয়ে হাত বারালো।আর ছোট্ট করে বল্লো.. -- আনান।  বলেই সামনের দিকে গেলো।নিহান এমন উত্তরে নিধীর দিকে তাকালো। নিধী ও তার দিকে তাকিয়ে বল্লো.. -- ও একটু এমন ই ইন্ট্রোভার্ট। আমাদোর সাথে ছারা তেমন কারো সাথে কথা বলে না।  নিহান ভ্রু কুচকে নিধীর দিকে তাকালো। তার পর আনান এর দিকে। মথা দুলয়িয়ে হু বলে ভিতরে চলে গেলো।বুশরা নিধীর আম্মু কে না দেখে কিচেন এ গেলো। উমি কিছু একটা করছিলে বুশরা এদিক ওদিক না তাকিয়ে এক দৌড়ে উনাকে পিছন থেকে জরিয়ে ধরে বল্লো..

#duet with @🇧🇩 AsᎥ𝖋🫀𝐒𝕦ᴍ𝔸𝕚𝚢𝐀🇧🇩,,জান গো শাসন কইরেন কিন্তু  কখনো  অবহেলা কইরেন না কারন আপনি একমাত্র ব্যক্তি যাকে ছারা আমি শূন্য । যাকে ছারা আমার বাড়ি কেন পুরো পৃথিবীর  খালি লাগে।। আপনি সেই ব্যক্তি যার সঙ্গে কথা না বললে রাতে ঘুম আসে না,,জীবনে ও ঘুম আসে না আপনি যদি জানতেন আপনাকে মিস করে  যতটা ছটফট করি তত একটা বাচ্চা খুদা লাগললে কম কান্না করে।আপনাকে যখন পাশে না পাই তখন কি করব বুঝতে পারি না। নিজেকে  সামলাতে অনেক কষ্ট হয়।মিস ইউ জান। আপনার একটু  অবহেলা জেন হৃদয়ে গিয়ে আঘাত করে যা সারাদিন চিৎকার করলেও  মানুষ কে বুঝাতে পারব না লাভ ইউ জান।আপনাকে  আমি নিজের থেকে ও বেশি ভালবাসি জান। আলাল কাছে চেয়ে আনছি আপনাকে আমি এমনি পাইনি,, আমার আলাল জানে,, একটা বাচ্চা চেয়ে বেশি কান্না করছি,,তাহাজ্জুদ বেকুলের মত কান্না করছি,,আলহামদুলিল্লাহ  আপনাকে পাইছি শুকরিয়া  আলহামদুলিল্লাহ A🥰s

রাহি মেহরিনের হাত টেনে বলল, চলো আপু তোমায় সবার সাথে পরিচয় করিয়ে দেই। আজ তুমি আমার স্পেশাল গেস্ট।  চুমকি হেসে বলল,ওগো রাহি সোনা  স্পেশাল না… একেবারে স্টার।  রাহি মেহরিনকে নিয়ে ড্রয়িং রুমে ঢোকে। ঘরটা আলোয় ঝলমল করছে, সারা বাড়ি চোখ ধাঁধানো সাজানোই সজ্জিত,  বাড়ির প্রিন্সেস এর বার্থডে বলে কথা। রাহি এসে সবার উদ্দেশ্যে বলে , Hello Ladies and Gentleman  attention please..  রাহির কথায় সবাই ওর দিকে তাকায়..  রাহি বলে Meet my special guest.. তখন সবার চোখ যায় মেহরিন এদিকে, চোখ যেন আটকে যায় কেবল এক জায়গায়—মেহরিনের মুখে। ঘরের ভেতরে গল্প করতে থাকা লোকজন একটু থেমে যায়। রামিম তখন কোল্ড ড্রিংকসের ট্রে হাতে, হঠাৎ থেমে মুগ্ধ চোখে তাকিয়ে থাকে। তার মনে হয় যেন কেউ হাতুড়ি পিটাচ্ছে , বুক ডুক ডুক করছে। আনমনে হাত চলে যায় বুকের বা পাশে । মুহূর্তেই এক দমকা  হাওয়া এসে ওলট পালট  করে দিয়েছে জীবনটা। আর পাশের সোফায় বসে থাকা আরাফ খান, যার কবিতা সবসময় কল্পনার প্রেয়সীকে খোঁজে—সেই মূহুর্তে চোখে স্পষ্ট ছায়া পায় তার! মেহরিন যেন তার লেখার এক জীবন্ত অনুবাদ। এই মেয়ে… কে?” আরাফ আনমনেই  প্রশ্ন করে। রামিম পাশে দাঁড়িয়ে ধীরে বলল, ওইটা… রাহির স্পেশাল গেস্ট।  আরাফ একটা মুচকি হাসি দিয়ে বলল, "হুঁ" সত্যি স্পেশাল বটে।  কিন্তু… কারো হৃদয়ে যে এখন থেকে তার জন্য টুংটাং  করে বাজবে সে কি জানবে?  সবার ধ্যান  ভাঙ্গে বাহির কথায়।  রাহির মুখ গর্বে ঝলমল -ওই যে বলছিলাম, আমার  আমার স্পেশাল গেস্ট। আমার পছন্দের একজন মানুষ আমার কিউটি আপু। তবে যাই বলো  আমার পছন্দ তো বরাবর সেরা। তার হাসিটা নিঃশব্দে ছড়িয়ে পড়লো পুরো ঘরে। রাহি হাত ধরে টেনে নিয়ে গেল মায়ের দিকে। রাহির মা তখনও তাকিয়ে ছিল মেহরিনের দিকে। মা দেখো এটাই আমার মেহেরিন আপু । মেহরিন সৌজন্যমূলক হাসি দিয়ে সালাম জানায় । রাহির মা হাসি মুখে উত্তর নেয়  তার পর বলে..  সাবিহা তালুকদার:   এটাই বুঝি তোমার মেহরিন আপু? রাহি হালকা মাথা ঝাঁকিয়ে সম্মতি জানাই।     মেহেরিন হালকা হাসে, আমরা এই বাড়িতে আজ প্রথম আসলো। প্রথমে একটু ভয় পেয়েছিল কে কিভাবে নেয়, এখানকার মানুষ কেমন এসব নিয়ে । তবে এখন ভয়টা চলে গেছে মনে হচ্ছে এখানকার প্রত্যেকটা মানুষই খুব ভালো ।  মেহরিন এগুলাই ভাবছিল আর তখন   সাবিহা তালুকদার : বাহ্! তুমি তো একেবারে মিষ্টি একটা মেয়ে! দেখে মনটা জুড়িয়ে গেল, মায়াভরা একটা মুখ, মিষ্টি হাসি আর এই সেই হাসিতে মন ভাঙার ওষুধ!” ঘরে থাকা দুই তরুণ—রামিম আর আরাফ, দুজনেই একসাথে যেন মনের মধ্যে আওড়ায়, "ভাঙবে তো বটেই... আমাদেরই মন আগে ভাঙবে" রাহি মায়ের দিকে চোখ টিপে বলল, বলেছিলাম না মা, আমার আপু কোনো সাধারণ মেয়ে না। সাবিহা তালুকদার  হেসে বললেন,  হ্যাঁ সেই তো  এই মেয়েকে দেখলে, যেন মনে হয় আলোর ছায়া নিয়ে কেউ হেঁটে আসছে। মেহরিন ওদের কথায় খুব লজ্জা পায়।তখনই চুমকি ফিসফিসিয়ে বলে  ভাই রে ভাই এরা তোকে যেভাবে দেখছে মনে হয় পাত্রী দেখতে এসেছে।  ওই যে দেখ , দুইটা ছেলে কেমন  কেবলার মত তাকিয়ে আছে  মনে হয় তোকে দেখে ওদের মনে প্রেমের ঘন্টা বেজে গেছে... চুমকি তখন ফিসফিসিয়ে বলে, এখানে সবাই অনেক ভালো। কিন্তু এত এত ভালো মানুষের ভিতরও এই রিদ তালুকদার এমন বদমেজাজি ঘাড় তেরা  কেমনে হইল রে দোস্ত ? শুনলাম   কেক আনতে গেছে রিদ ভাইয়া। এসে জানি আবার কি ঝামেলা পাকায় তোকে দেখে যদি রে'গে  যায়। আচ্ছা যা হবে পরে দেখা যাবে চল গিয়ে বসি। রাহি বলে আমার স্পেশাল গেস্ট আশায় আজকের পার্টি  আরো সুন্দর  হয়ে গেল ।  রামিম খেয়াল না করে বলে ফেলে, তুই আপু… এ তো একেবারে হৃদয়-হ্যাকার। আর পাশ থেকে আরাফ মুচকি হেসে বলে, আমি কবিতায় অনেক কিছু কল্পনা করেছিলাম… কিন্তু এমন হাসি, এমন চেহারা… কল্পনারও বাইরে। ওদের কথা শুনে  চুমকি একটু কেশে উঠে বলে, বাঁচাও আমার বন্ধুকে চারপাশে কত মৌমাছি উড়াউড়ি করছে কখন জানি এসে কামড় দেয়।  এত মুগ্ধতা না ছড়ালেই নয়। ঠিক তখনই মূল দরজার পাশে নরম শব্দে খুলে গেল কাঠের প্যানেল। রিদ তালুকদার হাতে কেকের বক্স, চোখে ক্লান্তি, মুখে স্বাভাবিক গাম্ভীর্য। মাথা নিচু করে ঘরে ঢুকছিল—জন্মদিনের ভিড়-ভাট্টা তার পছন্দ নয়। কিন্তু আজ তার কলিজার টুকরোর জন্মদিন । তাই আজ সে সব মেনে নিবে ওর যত আবদার যত আশা সব ।  চোখটা তুলে সামনে তাকায় রিদ.... তখনই থেমে গেল সময়। ড্রয়িং রুমের একপাশে  সোফাই বসে আছে রাহি  আর তার পাশে— এক অপরূপ তরুণী,  কালো হালকা শাড়িতে ঘেরা কোমল শরীর,চোখে কাজল, ঠোঁটে পিংক লিপস্টিক সবচাইতে বেশি যেটা নজর কাটছে সেটা হলো ঠোঁটের নিচে থাকা ওই  কালো তিলটা যেমনটা কবিতায় পড়ে, আর হাসিটা—একটুখানি বাঁকা, একটুখানি লাজুক, আর একেবারে হৃদয়ে বাজে।  রিদ হঠাৎ একটু যেন থমকে গেল। চোখে দৃষ্টি গাঢ় হলো। কিছু একটা খুঁজে ফেরে চোখ… ঠিক কী, সে জানে না। রাহি তখনই দৌড়ে গেল রিদের কাছে— #চলবে

part:32  হাতে একটা ইট Y/n'র, ওটাতে রক্ত লাগানো,এই মাত্র একটা ছেলের মাথায় চালিয়েছে ওটা, সবাই পরিস্থিতি বুঝে উঠার আগে আরেকটা ছেলের মাথায়ও চালালো, তারপর সাথে সাথে আরেকটার, লোকগুলো ফোন বের করে ভিডিও করতে শুরু করলো, কেউ Y/n'কে থামাচ্ছে না, না পরিস্থিতি বুঝতে ইচ্ছুক, taehyung ছুঁটে গিয়ে Y/n'র হাত ধরে নিলো, Y/n এতোটা রাগে যে আজ এদের একটাকেও যেনো জীবন্ত রাখবে না, এদিকে সেখানে ছয় টি ছেলে ছিলো Y/n'র এমন পাগলামি দেখে ওরা ভয় পেয়ে যায়, Y/n'র হাতে বেশ বড় সর ইটের একটা টুকরা আর ইচ্ছেমতো প্রহার করছে, তাই ছেলেগুলো আর সেখানে দাঁড়ালো না, তিনটা প্রাণ বাঁচানোর সুবিধার্থে আগেই পালিয়েছে আর যাদের মাথা ফেঁটেছে তারা মাথায় হাত দিয়ে বলতে বলতে পালালো --মাগো এ দেখি পাগল হইছে পালাও, এ তো দেখি মেরেই ফেলবে। Y/n:কই যাচ্ছিস তোরা? আয় না একাকিত্ব মেটাবি আমার? স্বামীর কমতি মেটাবি না আয় না? কোথায় যাচ্ছিস? Taehyung টান দিয়ে Y/n'র হাতের ইট টা সরিয়ে নিয়ে ফেলে দেয়। Taehyung:Y/n শান্ত হও, প্লিজ। Y/n:কেনো শান্ত হবো taehyung স্যার?কেনো শান্ত হবো বলেন আপনি?শান্ত আছি বলেই সবাই কথা শুনিয়ে যায় আমায়। সবাই বেচারি ভাবে, আরে হ্যাঁ আমার স্বামী ছেঁড়ে দিয়েছে আমায় তাই বলে কি আমার জীবন শেষ, আমি কি সবার ভোগপণ্য হয়ে গেছি, যে চাইবে আমাকে ছিঁড়ে খেতে আসবে, যে চাইবে আমায় কথা শুনিয়ে যাবে, এই দেখো এই, এই হলো আমাদের সমাজের লোক, এই দেখো সবাই ভিডিও করছে, আজকের ঘটনা ফেসবুকে আপলোড দিবে, আমাকে সেখানে কতো নামে ফুটিয়ে তুলবে #হিটলারদিদি #বিদ্রোহী নারি আর না জানি কি কি,সবাই আমায় নিয়ে জয় জয় করবে, কিন্তু তা শুধুই ফেসবুকে নিজেদের লাইক কমেন্ট বাড়ানোর সুবিধার্থে হবে,সবাইকে ওরা শো ওফ করবে যে ওরা কতো সচেতন, ন্যায়ের সাথে আছে, কিন্তু ওরা কতোটা সচেতন আপনি বলেন? আজকে এতো লোক থাকা সত্ত্বেও ওই লোকগুলো আমার সাথে খারাপ আচরন করছিলো কিন্তু কেউ সেদিকে ভ্রুক্ষেপ দেখায় নি,সবাই নিজেদেরকে নিয়েই ব্যাস্ত আর আমি এখন তার প্রতিবাদ করলাম বলে সবাই এখন এসে আমার কর্মকাণ্ড ভিডিও করছে, এরা যে পোস্ট করে বেশি বেশি লাইক কমেন্ট পাওয়ার জন্য একটা ভালো খবরের সন্ধান পেয়ে গেলো, কজন এগিয়ে এলো পরিস্থিতি সামলাতে?কজন জানতে চাইলো আসল সত্যটা? আজ এদের এমন নিম্ন অবস্থার কারনে দেশে ধর্ষণ, রাহাজানী, সন্ত্রাসী, জঙ্গি এসবের মতো অবৈধ কর্মকলাপ বেড়েই চলেছে, আমাদের সমাজের লোকগুলো যদি শো ওফ করতে ব্যাস্ত না হয়ে সত্যতার মোকাবিলা করতো তবে প্রতিদিন কোনো না কোনো মেয়েকে ধর্ষনের স্বিকার হতে হতো না, যেখানে সেখানে বোমা হামলা হতো না,চুরি ছিনতাই বাড়তো না, কিন্তু আফসোস আমাদের সমাজের লোকগুলো ধীরে ধীরে বিলুপ্তির দিকে গড়াচ্ছে, আজকে যদি আমি ওই লোকগুলোর প্রতিবাদ না করতাম তবে কোনো একসময় আমিও ধর্ষণের স্বিকার হয়ে লাশ হয়ে পড়ে থাকতাম কোনো ঝোঁপের আড়ালে, তখনও লোকগুলো আমাকে নিয়ে নিউজ পোস্ট করতো, ফেসবুকে আমাকে নিয়ে দুঃখ প্রকাশ করতো কিন্তু একবার এরা এটা ভাবতোও না যদি এরা একটু সচেতন হতো তবে আজকাল আমাদের মা বোনেরা যখন তখন যেখানে সেখানে ধর্ষনের স্বিকার হতো না, আমিও চেয়েছিলাম আজ আর আট-দশ টা মেয়ের মতো এদের এড়িয়ে চলে যেতে কিন্তু পরক্ষণেই বুঝতে পারলাম এই সমাজে একটা একা মেয়েকে লোক বাঁচতে দিতে চায় না শান্তিতে, তাই বাঁচতে হলে নিজের সংগ্রাম নিজেই করতে হবে।  কথাগুলো শুনে লোকগুলো ঠায় দাঁড়িয়ে আছে ওর দিকে তাকিয়ে, তবে ভিডিও করা এখনও কেউই বন্ধ করে নি, হয়তো সমাজের লোকগুলো আজকে বিলুপ্তির একদম শেষ দিকে চলে গেছে তাই এমন কথাও ওদের বিবেকে বাঁধছে না, Y/n এবার ইট নিয়ে ওদের দিকেও তেঁড়ে যায়, ঝাঁঝালো কন্ঠে বলে উঠে। Y/n : সবাই চলে যাও এখান থেকে নয়তো আমি সবার মাথা ফাঁটিয়ে দেবো। সবাইকে মেরে ফেলবো। লোকগুলো স্থান ত্যাগ করলো ধীরে ধীরে, taehyung এবার Y/n'কে শান্ত করার চেষ্টা করলো। Taehyung: মিস Y/n শান্ত হন আপনি প্লিজ, সমাজটা যে সত্যিই আজ বিলুপ্তির দিকে, এদের সাথে কথা বলে কোনো লাভনেই, আপনি এখানে দাঁড়ান আমি আপনার জন্য পানি নিয়ে আসি। Y/n : লাগবে না স্যার, আমি ঠিক আছি, এই যে রিক্সাওয়ালা চাচা দাঁড়ান। Taehyung: রিক্সায় যাবেন কেনো? আমিওতো ভার্সিটি যাচ্ছি আমার সাথে চলুন। Y/n : ধন্যবাদ, কিন্তু আমি নিজের সবকিছু একাই ম্যানেজ করতে চাই। কথাটা বলে Y/n রিক্সা করে চলে গেলো, taehyung তাকিয়ে রইলো ওর যাওয়ার পানে। __ ___ ___  ভার্সিটিতে আজ সারাদিন taehyung Y/n'কে লক্ষ্য করলো, অন্যদিনের মতো আজকে আর কথা বলছে না হাসছেও না Y/n, হয়তো সবকিছুই হাসিমুখে মানিয়ে নিতে এখন ধীরে ধীরে ক্লান্ত হয়ে পড়ছে ওকে দেখে এমন সব কথা মস্তিষ্কে নাড়া দিলো taehyung'র। সত্যিই একটা মেয়েকে লোক সমাজে একা বাস করতে দিতে চায় না, সবদিক থেকে ওর বাঁচা মুসকিল করে তুলে, taehyung'র এসব ভাবনায়ই ভার্সিটির সময় শেষ হলো, Y/n'কে বেড়িয়ে যেতে দেখলো taehyung.......         চলবে... বেশি করে কপি লিংক করে দিলে কি হয় 💔

Jungkook যখন yn কে সামলাতে ব্যাস্ত তখনি তার হাতে টান পড়লো। Jungkook চোখ মেলে দেখলো সবাই yn কে টেনে নিয়ে যাচ্ছে। না ওরা কোনো yn কে নিয়ে যাচ্ছে না বরং Jungkook এর আত্নাটাকে টেনে হিচরে নিয়ে যাচ্ছে।  yn Jungkook এর দিকে তাকিয়ে বাচ্চাদের মতো কান্না করছে। yn এর অসহায় চাহনি Jungkook এর ভিতরটাকে ধুমড়ে মুচড়ে দিচ্ছে। Jungkook কি করে বুঝাবে তার ভিতরে যে রক্ত***ক্ষরণ হচ্ছে তা বাইরের আঘাতের থেকেও অনেক ভয়াবহ। সে জানে yn তার জন্যই কাঁদছে কিন্তু সেটা সে ছাড়া কেউ বুঝবে না। প্রকৃতির খেলায় সে আজ অসহায় পথিক যে কিনা নিজের চোখেই নিজের আত্নার বিসর্জন দেখছে। ভিতরের আত্নাটা ছটফট করলেও শরীরে এক ফোটা ও শক্তি নেই,মুখ ফুটে বলতে পারছে না আমার জানকে ছেড়ে দাও। Jungkook এর আত্মার আর্তনাদ কেউ শুনতে পাচ্ছে না।   জানো এই মূহুর্তে এখন Jungkook এর কার কথা মনে পরছে? হ্যা জিমিনের কথা মনে পড়ছে। পৃথিবীতে এই একটাই মানুষ ছিলো যে কিনা Jungkook এর না বলা কথা বুঝতে পারতো, কিন্তু Jungkook আজ নিজের স্বার্থে তাকে ন***ড়কে ফেলে দিয়েছে। আজ জিমিন যদি থাকতো Jungkook নিশ্চিতে ম****রতে পারতো। Jungkook এর আঘাতটা নেহাৎ কম নই কিন্তু yn কে এই অবস্থায় রেখে সে ম****রেও শান্তি পাবে না। কথাগুলো ভাবতে ভাবতেই Jungkook জ্ঞা**ন হারালো। Jungkook কে হাসপাতালে পাঠিয়ে দেওয়া হলো কিন্তু এদিকে yn এর করুন অবস্থা।  yn মেয়ে বলে সবাই বলেছিলো ওর গায়ে হাত না তুলে পুলিশে দিয়ে দিতে কিন্তু ইরা তাতে সায় দেইনি। ইরা এই সুযোগটাকে মিস করতে চাইনি তাই বলল ইরা : মা**রের বিচার মার দিয়েই হবে। yn অসহায়ের মতো এদিক-ওদিক দেখছে সবাই তাকে মারার প্ল্যান করছে সেটা তার মাথায় এখনো ঢুকেনি। সেতো Jungkook এর চিন্তায় চিন্তিত রাগের মাথায় করে ফেললেও Jungkook এর র**ক্ত দেখে আর নিজেকে ঠিক রাখতে পারছে না। মনে মনে হাজার বার প্রার্থনা করছে Jungkook এর যেনো কিছু না হয়। কারণ সেও যে Jungkook কে প্রাণের চেয়ে বেশি ভালোবাসে।  yn : Jungkook ঠিকই বলতো আমি সত্যিই বোকা কি করে কি করে ফেল্লাম? জানি পাপ করেছি,আমি পাপি তবুও তোমার কাছে দুই হাত তুলে ভিক্ষা চাইছি খুদা তুমি Jungkook কে সুস্থ করে দাও, তেমার কাছে আর কখনো কিছু চাইবো না,তুমি শুধু আমার Jungkook কে ঠিক করে দাও।কেউ না জানুক তুমিতো জানো আমি Jungkook কে ঠিক কতটা ভালোবাসি। আমার জীবনের বিনিময়ে হলেও তুমি Jungkook কে সুস্থ করে দাও। ইরার মুখে বিজয়ের হাসি, yn কে প্রথম আঘাতটা ইরায় করলো। yn Jungkook এর হাতে মা****র খেলেও এমন মা*****রে*র সাথে পরিচিত না এক একটা আ**ঘাতে yn মৃত্যু যন্ত্রণা অনুভব করছে। হঠাৎ করেই ইরা বলে উঠলো -এবার তুমায় কে বাঁচাবে yn? yn এর নামটা শুনার সাথে সাথেই কেউ একজন ২২০ বোল্টের শক খেলো। ছেলেটি অবাক হয়ে বললো -কি নাম বললে? ইরা না বুঝেই উওর দিলো -কেন yn! সাথে সাথেই ছেলেটি কাউকে কিছু বুঝার সুযোগ না দিয়ে yn কে নিয়ে সেখান থেকে উধাও হয়ে যায়।সবার থেকে নিরাপদ দূরত্বে গিয়ে বললো -ম্যাডাম আপনার লাগেনি তো?  yn অবাক হলো তবুও ছেলেটার অস্থিরতা দেখে উওর দিতে বাধ্য হলো yn : লেগেছে তবে সামান্য। কিন্তু আপনি কে? আমি তো আপনাকে চিনতে পারছি না, আমাকে বাচালেন কেন?  ছেলেটি বলে উঠলো -আমি Teahyung Jungkook ভাইয়ের এসিস্ট্যান্ট আমি জানি আপনি কে। সেদিন Jungkook ভাইয়ের মুখে আপনার নাম শুনেছি দেখা করার ইচ্ছে ছিলো কিন্তু সৌভাগ্য হয়ে উঠেনি। আজ এইভাবে এই অবস্থায় দেখা হবে ভাবতে পারনি। যাইহোক ম্যাডাম আমি আপনার মনের কথা বুঝতে পারছি আপনি চিন্তা করবেন না ভাই সুস্থ হয়ে যাবে। আপনি শান্ত হোন সব ঠিক হয়ে যাবে। চলুন আপনাকে বাসায় দিয়ে আসি এখানে থাকা আপনার জন্য নিরাপদ নই। yn : বাসায় যাব কি করে? আমি তো Jungkook এর বাসায় থাকি কোন মুখে ওই বাড়িতে যাবো?  teahyung ব্যাপারটা বুঝতে পারলো তারপর সে একটা বসার সামনে গিয়ে yn কে নামিয়ে দিয়ে বললো -আজ আপনি এই বসায় থাকুন এটা আমার বাসা আপনার কোনো অসুবিধা হবে না। আসলে বাইরে আপনার জন্য অনেক বিপদ ওত পেতে বসে আছে। তাই বাসা থেকে বের হওয়াটা ঠিক হবে না।আপনি প্লিজ ঘরেই থাকুন সবাই আপনার উপর ক্ষেপে আছে। বাইরে কে কখন কি করবে বলা যায় না।ভাই সুস্থ না হওয়া পর্যন্ত এখানেই থাকুন। teahyung একটা মেয়েকে ডেকে বললো -ম্যাডামকে আমার রুমে নিয়ে যাও। শোনো ম্যাডামের দিকে খেয়াল রাখবে। আজ বাসায় কাউকে ঢুকতে দিবে না আর ম্যাডামের যা যা লাগবে সব এনে দিবে। ম্যাডামের যেন কোনো অসুবিধা না হয় ঠিক আছে? #তুমি_আমার_সন্ধ্যাপ্রদীপ♡ || part~33|| যেখানে ভুলবশত তুলে আনা তাকে। কিন্তু এবার? এবার বুঝি ওকেই বলি হতে হবে? y/n চোখ বুজে আরো একবার প্রার্থনা করল। y/n in mind:দরকার পড়লে আমায় মে*রে ফেলুক আল্লাহ, শুধু সম্মানে যেন হাত না দেয়। kai, jungkook, jimin,chaeunwoo ক্রমাগত তার নাকের ডগায় এলোমেলো হাঁটছে। একেজনের ভাবভঙ্গি চিন্তিত, উৎকণ্ঠিত। দ্বিতীয় তলার এই ফ্ল্যাটে ঘর মোট চারটি। বসার ঘরে কাজী সাহেব বন্দী। বাকী শোবার ঘরের একটিতে taehyung। সে তখনো কান্নাকাটি করছে। jennieকে পাওয়ার একটুখানি আশা,এমন নিদারুণ ভাবে চুরমার হয়ে যাওয়ার হাহা*কারে কণ্ঠনানী ব্যস্ত। y/nr মায়া হয় সে কান্নায়। মুখবিবরের সংকীর্ণতা বাড়ে। আপুটা এমন না করলেই পারতো না? ওকে তো জোর করে বিয়ে দেওয়া হয়নি। খালুজান নিজে তার সামনে দাঁড়িয়ে প্রশ্ন করেছিলেন, কাউকে পছন্দ করে কিনা। আপু নির্দ্বিধায় জানিয়েছিল 'না'। তবে এই ছেলে এলো কোত্থেকে? এমন করুণ কান্না, হা-হুতাশ তো মিথ্যে হতে পারেনা। কাউকে হারানোর শোকে, এমন আহাজারি তো কোনও ভুল মানুষের নয়। উনি নিশ্চয়ই মন থেকে ভালোবাসতেন। y/n দীর্ঘশ্বাস টানল। ফের চাইল বাকীদের দিকে। মাত্রাধিক ভ*য়ে একটু আগে জ্ঞান হারিয়েছিল ও। চেতনা ফিরলে হাত-পায়ের বাঁধন খুঁজে পায়নি। তবে বাঁধা স্থান চিনচিন করছে যন্ত্র*নায়। দাগ পড়েছে হয়ত। কী নির্মম ভাবে বেঁধেছে আল্লাহ মালুম। সাথে ওরাও চুপচাপ। সেই থেকে শুধু পায়চারি করছে। কেউ কোনও প্রশ্নই তো করছেনা। এতেই আকাশ ছুঁচ্ছে y/nr। এই নির্বাক থাকাই যেন দানবীয় ঝড়ের পূর্বাভাস। দলবদ্ধ পরিকল্পনা সাজিয়েই কী হামলা করবে ওর ওপর? এতক্ষণে তো তার অক্ষত থাকার কথা নয়। কী করতে চাইছে ওরা? y/nr মাথায় হঠাৎই নেকড়ে রূপে ধরা দিলো পাঁচজন। এক সে রক্তে মাংসের মানুষ, আর চারপাশে ঘুরছে এই হিংস্র নেকড়ের দল। আই- ঢাই বেঁধে একটা সময় ঝাঁপিয়ে আসবে গায়ে। নিষ্ঠুর ভাবে ছিড়েখুঁড়ে খাবে। y/nr গলা শুকিয়ে যায় ভেবেই। মাথা চক্কর কাটে দূর্বলতায়। একটু পানির জন্য গলবিলটা ছটফটায় খুব। বিধিবাম। চেয়ে নেওয়ার সাহস টুকুও হয় না। এদিকে বিপাকে পড়েছে jungkook। চিন্তায় তার মস্তিষ্কের শিরা লাফাচ্ছে। ভীষণ বাজে ভাবে ব্যথা উঠেছে কপালে।taehyung কে দেওয়া কথা না রাখতে পারার ব্যর্থতায় কলিজার ছিড়ে যাচ্ছে। মানুষটা সে পাষাণ বলে আখ্যায়িত হলেও, বন্ধু আর মায়ের জন্য শতভাগ খাঁটি।kai আর jiminকে দুমদাম চিবিয়ে খাওয়ার jungkook রাগে ফোসফোস করল। ইচ্ছে চলছে ভেতরে। ওদের একটু অসতর্কতায় কী ঝামেলাই না বাঁধল।এমন বুঝলে সে নিজে যেত। কোনও দিন নির্বোধ দুটোকে পাঠাত না। এই ভেড়াগুলোকে নাকী এলাকার মানুষ ভ*য়ও পায় আবার। taehyung er কাছে jin বসে। ওকে সামলানোর চেষ্টা করছে ছেলেটা।হাতে একটুখানি সময় মিললেও ফের মেয়েটাকে আনতে যেতে পারত। কিন্তু যতক্ষণে সত্যিটা জেনেছে ততক্ষণে সব শেষ।করার কিচ্ছু নেই। ওদিকে বসার ঘরে বন্দি কাজী। এদিকে এই মেয়ে। কোনটাকে নিয়ে কী করবে ভাবলেই মাথা এলোমেলো হয়ে যাচ্ছে jungkookr।jungkook আড়চোখে একবার y/nr দিক চাইল।অগোছালো কালো চুলে তার পিঠ, গালের একাংশ আড়ালে। দুই হাঁটু বক্ষে চেপে কবুতর ছানার ন্যায় বসে। মেয়েটা যে কী সাংঘাতিক মাত্রার ভীতু ওর বুঝতে বাকী নেই। তাই আপাতত জিজ্ঞাসাবাদ বন্ধ।আর করেও বা কি? যেখানে সকল পদক্ষেপ রুদ্ধ, সেখানে মেয়েটিকে ঘাঁটিয়ে কী লাভ? jungkook দৃষ্টি ফেরায়। মেজাজ শান্ত করতে সিগারেট ধরাল। হুরহুরে ভঙিতে কামড়ায় ছড়িয়ে পড়ল সিগারেটের ধোঁয়া। খুব আস্তে, নীচুস্বরে কেশে উঠল y/n। একে তৃষার্ত সে, দুইয়ে ধোয়ার আক্রমণে গলা শুদ্ধ জ্বলে উঠল যেন। jungkook এই কাশির কারণ বোঝেনি। বুঝলেও কিছু করত কী না সন্দেহ। নিরুৎসাহিত সে সিগারেট ঠোঁটে চেপে কাঠের চেয়ারে বসল গিয়ে। বন্ধ জানলার এক পাশের কপাট খুলতেই বর্ষার ছাট এসে চোখমুখে লাগে।jungkook মনোযোগী চোখে প্রকৃতি দেখল। অন্ধকারে হাত খুঁজে পাওয়া মুশকিল। বৃষ্টির ধার কমেনি। সম্পূর্ণ ঘর নিস্তব্ধ। হাঁটা ব্যাতীত, কারো টা-টু শব্দ নেই।kai চেয়েও কিছু বলতে পারছেনা। দু দুটো অকাজ করে অপরাধীর ন্যায় চুপ সে। কখন আবার বিটুটা ফুঁসে ওঠে ওর ওপর।দলের মধ্যে jungkook চড় সেই বেশি খায়। এইত, তখনকার চড়ে এখনও গাল ঝিমঝিম করছে কেমন। ও ঘর থেকে আচমকা তারস্বরে ফোন বাজল। কাজী সাহেবের বাটন ফোনের শব্দ, মাথা ধরানো ক্রিং ক্রিং আওয়াজ। সেই শব্দে y/n শক্তিহীন শরীরটা ফের কাঁপে। নড়েচড়ে ওঠে। ভয়ার্ত, নজর চারপাশে বোলায়। সবকিছু আগের মত দেখে শ্রান্ত ভাবে চোখ বুজল। চক্ষুপটে হানা দিলো sukr পাপহীন আর মমতাময়ী সালমা বেগমের আননখানি। আচ্ছা, সবাই কি জেনে গিয়েছে সে বাড়িতে নেই? মণি নিশ্চয়ই খুঁজছে খুব? suk কাঁদছে বোধ হয়। বাকীরাও কি খুঁজছে ওকে? আপুর বিয়েটা কী হয়েছে? ছেলেগুলো যদি এখন ওকে রেপ করে মেরে ফেলে?তাহলে তো আর কোনও দিন ফেরা হবেনা ওদের কাছে। #fyp #foryou

People with sociopath friends? Why are you friends with them? My roommate from college is a diagnosed sociopath and he's the most reliable friend I have. We met freshman year when I found him sitting alone writing down what people did when they laughed. He told me straight up that he didn't really get people, but trying to learn. I thought he was joking until I saw him practice smiling in the mirror before parties. What's weird is that he remembers everything I've ever told him. When my mom got sick, he showed up with groceries and said, you won't remember to eat properly. I've researched nutritious meals that are easy to make. Not a hint of emotion, just logic. He once asked why people cry at funerals if the person is already dead, but then he drove six hours to attend my grandpa's funeral because social support improves grief outcomes. His girlfriend dumped him because he forgot Valentine's Day. He genuinely didn't understand why one random day matters more than others. The next day he made a spreadsheet of all holidays with reminders set weeks ahead. Last week he called me at 3:00am asking is it normal to feel something warm in your chest when your son smiles at you? His wife just had a baby and I think he might actually be experiencing love for the first time. He's reading parenting books every night. People think sociopaths are all dangerous, but my friend just sees the world differently. He Chooses to be good because it's logical. And sometimes that's more reliable than emotional goodness that comes and goes.

My brother's bad choices LED to the worst night of our lives. He started hanging out with the wrong crowd after dropping out of school. Mom was worried sick because he'd come home at 3 a m. Carrying expensive stuff he couldn't afford on his part time job. Designer clothes, new phones, gold chains. We knew something wasn't right, but he'd get angry whenever we asked. One night while he was out, I found a huge duffel bag hidden under his bed. Inside were dozens of phones still in their boxes with price tags from different stores. I knew right away they were stolen. My hands were shaking as I loaded them into my car and drove to the police. When my brother found out, he completely lost it. His face turned ghostly white. He screamed that those weren't his. He was just holding them for someone. He had to pay $25,000 to replace them. Or else. You don't understand what you've done, he kept saying, pacing like a caged animal. Three days later, mom called me, crying so hard I could barely understand her. My brother was in the hospital. They found him beaten half to death behind an abandoned warehouse, zip tied to a chair. His left leg was shattered in three places. Through tears, he told me the guys he was working for did this as a warning. They said next time would be worse. They wanted me to know exactly what would happen if I ever Lost their stuff again, he whispered. That night changed everything. My brother moved across the country to start fresh. Now he works as a youth counselor, helping kids avoid the same mistakes that almost cost him his life. He says turning in those phones saved him from an even darker path.

Showers with my 14 year old son and didn't expect him to do this to me. I am a 37 year old woman and I know what you're thinking when you hear that my 14 year old son showers with me. Right. Well, I have a good reason for it. We both share the same bathroom and bedroom. First, I hesitated to admit this online because of the looks and judgmental comments I would receive from strangers. But here it goes. It all started three years ago when my husband suddenly left us without any explanation. It was a complete shock. We had been married for over 15 years and he seemed happy. Until one day he packed his bags and disappeared. All he said to us was, I'm going to buy milk at the gas station. Be right back. He never came back. The kids were devastated, especially my youngest, Max. He clung to me more than ever, seeking comfort wherever he could find it. At night, Max would come into my room, shivering from the cold, begging for a warm blanket. As much as I wanted to send him back to his own room, I couldn't bear to see him so vulnerable. So gradually, Max moved closer to my side, eventually ending up sleeping beside me, sometimes even cuddled up to me. Over time, I began to notice that Max wouldn't leave my side during the day either, whether it was taking a shower or brushing his teeth. Max was always there, watching closely. I tried to ignore it, hoping he would outgrow it like most teenage behaviours. However, as days turned into weeks and then into months, I realised that this wasn't going away anytime soon. One night, while I was taking a shower, Max asked if he could join me. I asked why, and he said that all the kids at school say I have a level 9 gas. I don't know what that means, but I was shocked. At first I hesitated, unsure if it was appropriate or healthy. But looking at him, so small and fragile, I knew deep down that I couldn't say no. And so began our new ritual. Everything was going fine, just normal showers with mother and son. Until I dropped my soap and it fell. You can now check if there's a part two by pressing share and more!

Gave my stepmom the perfect Mother's Day gift, then watched her face as she realized what it really meant. When my dad married Cassandra, I was 11. Mom had been gone for 13 months. Melanoma that spread faster than anyone expected. One day, she was complaining about a headache, and 82 days later, I was standing at her grave in a black dress that still had the tags on. Dad waited exactly one year before bringing Cassandra home. She worked at his investment firm, client relations. Perfect teeth, blonde hair that never move. The kind of woman who wore heels to other people's barbecues. She makes me happy again, dad explained, his voice gentle but firm. I need you to try, Emily. So I tried. I helped Cassandra move in, carrying boxes of designer shoes to the closet where Mom's gardening clothes used to hang. I nodded politely when she rearranged our furniture, replacing family photos with abstract art that opened up the space. I even smiled when she transformed Mom's vegetable garden into a meditation patio, because growing our own food is so provincial. For three years, I performed the role of grateful stepdaughter. I attended her corporate events wearing the dresses she bought me. I tolerated her friends who cooed about how mature I was. For 14, I kept my grief hidden behind perfect grades and false smiles. Dad didn't notice when I stopped laughing, too busy with Cassandra's social calendar and the new clients she brought in. Too distracted by their couples retreats and wine club memberships. Meanwhile, I slept with Mom's sweater under my pillow until it stopped smelling like her. Cassandra tried. In her way. She bought me expensive birthday gifts, always things she would want. She hosted elaborate dinner parties and introduced me as our daughter to important people who never remembered my name. She even started a college fund for me, making sure everyone knew about her generosity. But when I got my period for the first time, it was Google that taught me what to do. When I had nightmares about mom dying, it was the family dog who comforted me. Breaking point came during sophomore year. I was cast as the lead in the school play, the first thing I'd felt passionate about since mom died. Opening night fell on the same evening as Cassandra's charity gala. Obviously, you'll need to skip the performance, she said, not looking up from her phone. The Richardson's are bringing their son. He's at Princeton. Connections. Emily. Dad started to object, then stopped when Cassandra placed her hand on his arm. It's just a high school play, he finally said. There will be others. I went to my room and pulled out the antique jewelry box mom had left me. Inside was her wedding ring, a lock of my baby hair, and a journal I'd never opened. Too afraid of confronting her final thoughts. That night, through tears, I read it, covered a cover most Of it was what you'd expect. Her hopes for my future memories she cherished. Advice she wouldn't be able to give in person. But the last entry, dated two weeks before she died, was different. If you're reading this, Emily, I need you to know about the safe deposit box. The key is taped inside this cover. What you find there will change everything. I'm so sorry. Key was small and silver, with the bank's name etched into it. The next day, I skipped school and went to First National. The manager recognized me. Mom's family had banked there for generations. Your mother said you'd come eventually, he said, leading me to the vault. Inside the box was a USB drive, several folders of documents, and a letter addressed to me in Mom's handwriting. My dearest Emily. It began. By now, Cassandra has probably worked her way into your lives completely. I've known about her for years. I couldn't fit what happens next in this short video. Watch the rest down below.

Did your parents fail you? My dad missed my graduation for a job interview. Mom promised he'd make it, but kept checking her phone anxiously during the entire ceremony. I felt my heart sink when I scanned the crowd and didn't see his face anywhere. After walking across that stage, I gripped my phone, waiting for something. No texts, no calls. Complete silence. Mom couldn't look me in the eyes. When I found her afterward, she hugged me way too tight and whispered, he really tried, sweetheart. My chest burned with anger. I couldn't hide anymore. At my graduation party, relatives kept asking about dad. Mom cycled through increasingly desperate excuses. Traffic jam, work emergency, car trouble, each lie more pathetic than the last. I watched her stumble through explanations while my shame grew deeper. My friend Jake pulled me aside and asked, you doing okay, man? I just laughed and said, he's been doing this since I was 7 years old, because it was absolutely true. He missed my championship basketball game where I scored the winning shot. Missed my debate team finals when I took first place. Even missed my 18th birthday party last year. Said he had to work late again that night. After everyone finally left, I sat alone staring at my diploma. Mom tried approaching me, but I cut her off immediately. I said, grabbing my car keys, I've heard every excuse before. I drove to my old elementary school playground and sat on the Same swing where dad used to push me before work completely consumed his life. Before he became just a distant voice sometimes heard. Coming home at 2:00am, something inside me finally broke that night. All the anger I'd bottled up for years spilled over at once. I pulled out my phone and texted him. Congratulations on showing me exactly where I rank in your priorities. Message delivered. Read immediately. When I got home after midnight, Dad's car was sitting in our driveway. I found him hunched over our kitchen table. Head.

My wife gave our son a different name on the birth certificate. Her ex's. When I confronted her, she laughed. Yeah, he's not even yours. What are you going to do? Divorce me? This is a no fault state. I'm taking half. Loser. I didn't say a word. I just got a DNA test, hired a lawyer and started packing. Three months later she was outside my building, sobbing, homeless and begging me to. I thirty four m am still processing how one piece of paper changed everything. It's been just five days since my son was born. My wife, Vanessa, 31F, was discharged yesterday and I was sorting through the paperwork from the hospital. Birth certificate, insurance forms, the usual. That's when I saw it. The name on the birth certificate. Not James Taylor, like we'd agreed. Instead, Alexander Reynolds Taylor. Alexander. The name hit me like a truck. That was her ex's name. Vanessa, what's this? I asked, walking into the bedroom where she was resting with a baby. The birth certificate says Alexander, not James. She glanced up, then looked back at her phone. Oh yeah, last minute change of heart. Alexander sounds better. Alexander, like your ex? Something shifted in her face. A cold calculation replaced the exhaustion of new motherhood. Surprised you caught that so quickly, she said with a small, ugly laugh. Why would you name our son after your ex? Because he's not our son, Mark. He's Alex's son. The room seemed to Tilt what? You heard me. The baby isn't yours. Alex and I have been seeing each other for about a year. I stared at her, blood rushing in my ears. What are you going to do about it? Divorce me. She laughed coldly. This is a no fault state. I get half of everything either way. The house, your savings, plus child support. She turned back to her phone. Stay and play daddy, or leave and pay. Either way, I win. I didn't say a word, didn't scream, didn't throw things. Just turned around and walked out of the room. My first call was to a DNA testing facility. They could see me tomorrow. Second call was to a law firm specializing in divorce cases. The receptionist heard the urgency in my voice and squeezed me in for a consultation the same afternoon. Jessica Winters was exactly what I needed. Experienced, direct, and strategically minded. No fault. Divorce doesn't mean what your wife thinks it means, she explained after hearing my situation. It just means you don't need to prove wrongdoing to get divorced. It doesn't guarantee her half your assets, especially with evidence of fraud. Fraud? Paternity fraud. Putting you on the birth certificate of another man's child knowingly. That's fraud. Her admission about taking half your assets shows intent. We can work with that. Jessica outlined a strategy. Get the D N A. Test. Gather financial records, especially proof of assets I had before marriage. Secure valuables and Irreplaceable items. Find new housing. Most importantly, don't tip your hand. Let her think she's winning, Jessica advised. The more complacent she is, the better. Three days later, the DNA test confirmed what I already knew. The baby wasn't mine. I spent the next week securing my most important documents and possessions in a storage unit, researching apartments, and meticulously documenting our finances. Our home was mostly purchased with money from my software business that had sold before we married. Premarital asset. Jessica confirmed. This would be critical, she advised, urging me to gather all documentation showing the source of the down payment and mortgage payments. One week later, while Vanessa was at her postnatal checkup with her mother, I executed the plan. The movers arrived at 9:00am sharp, efficiently packing my pre marriage furniture and personal belongings. By 11:00, they were gone. I had my name removed from all utilities, left the divorce papers on the dining table with a note, all communication through my attorney, and drove to my new apartment. The sense of calm was surreal. Not the reaction she expected, I'm sure. Update 1 72 hours later. Well, it's been a ride. Thanks for the comments and DMs. Good to know I'm not completely off my rocker for reacting the way I did. 72 hours refers to when I'm writing this. The main confrontation happened Wednesday afternoon, same day as the birth certificate discovery. Vanessa returned home from her appointment around two PM. According to our Neighbour Ted, who texted me. There was a lot of screaming about 15 minutes later. Then the barrage began. 21 missed calls, 31 texts, all blocked. I read a few before blocking her. What the hell did you do? You can't just leave like this. This isn't how we're supposed to handle this. You were supposed to stay and support us or pay from afar, not fight. You'll regret this.

When did you realise your parents were bad at parenting? When I turned 12, my mom handed me a credit card with my name on it. Not for emergencies, for groceries. She sat me down at our kitchen table with this massive stack of manufacturer coupon she'd been collecting and said, you're smart enough to handle the shopping now. I trust you more than myself with money. At first, I felt so incredibly grown up, walking through Walmart alone every Tuesday and Friday, pushing a full sized cart while other kids my age were begging their parents for candy. They'd stare at me like I was some kind of alien. The cashiers all knew me by name within a month. Back again, honey, Linda would say, automatically helping me reach the heavy detergent bottles on the top shelf. She started setting aside the markdown meat for me when it was about to expire. I Learned which cereals had the best protein to cost ratio, how to spot when the rotisserie chickens were about to be discount wanted. I could stretch $80 into two full weeks of meals for our family of four, and I was genuinely proud of it. I had this whole elaborate system. Mondays, I'd plan the weekly menu based on store flyers and whatever coupons we had. Tuesdays, I'd hit Walmart for the bulk items and household essentials. Fridays, I'd go to the smaller grocery store for fresh produce and whatever we'd run out of during the Week, their parents would see me in the cereal aisle comparing unit prices with a calculator, and they do these obvious double takes. One woman actually followed me around the store for 20 minutes, then approached me by the checkout. Sweetie, are you shopping for your family? She asked really gently. When I nodded and showed her my organized list with meal plans written in the margins, she looked absolutely horrified. She asked if my parents were okay, if there was an adult she could call for me. I just told her what mom always said, that I was mature for my age, and this was a good life experience that would serve me well as an adult. During parent teacher conferences in October, my teacher mentioned how I always ate the free breakfast at school, even though we technically weren't on the reduced lunch program. She's incredibly responsible for her age.

Identical twins. What's the most embarrassing situation where you've been mistaken for your twin? When my sister Tracy and I were born, our parents dressed us differently so they could tell us apart. As we grew older, we embraced being identical by pulling harmless pranks like switching seats in class or pretending to be each other at the mall. But everything changed senior year when Tracy started dating our high school star football player, Noah. I never liked Noah. He had this arrogant smirk and treated everyone like they were beneath him. He'd shove freshmen into lockers and mock the band kids during lunch. Tracy insisted he was different when they were alone, but I saw how he'd grab her arm too roughly when she talked to other guys. One night, Tracy came home with tears streaming down her face. Her sleeve was pulled up, revealing finger shaped bruises. Noah had gotten jealous when she was assigned a male lab partner. She begged me not to tell her parents, saying it was a one time thing. He'd apologized, bought her flowers, promised it would never happen again. But it did happen again and again. Each time, Tracy had a new excuse. I fell during cheerleading. I bumped into a door. I watched my confident, bubbly sister become a shell of herself. She stopped wearing her favorite crop tops, started flinching at loud noises, and came homecoming night. Tracy was supposed to go with Noah, but she had a 102 degree Fever. Our parents insisted she stay home. That's when I had an idea. I put on her dress, styled my hair exactly like hers, and went to the dance instead. Noah was waiting by the punch bowl.

What has your pet accidentally conditioned you to do? My dog, Luna, trained me to wake up at exactly 2:47 a m. Every night to let her out. And that's how I discovered my husband was poisoning me. It started when Luna was a puppy. She had the tiniest bladder and would wine at my side of the bed at the same time every night for three years. My internal clock became so precise that I'd wake up seconds before her whining started. My husband and Jake always slept through it. Heavy sleeper. He'd mumble in the morning. Lucky me. Luna would do her business quickly. Then we'd both go back to bed. It became our routine. One night, I woke up at 2:47 as usual, but Luna wasn't there. I found her in the kitchen, standing perfectly still, staring at Jake. He was at the counter with his back to me, stirring something into a glass of water. Honey, I whispered. You okay? He spun around, nearly dropping the glass. Oh, you scared me. Just getting some water. Go back to bed. But Luna wouldn't move. She kept staring at him with this intense focus I'd never seen before. Her tail was low, ears back. Not scared. Alert. What's in the glass? I asked. Just water and some antacid. My stomach's been bothering me. He drank it quickly and headed back to bed. Luna followed me upstairs, but she kept looking back at the kitchen. The next night, same Routine. I woke up at 2:47, but again, Luna wasn't by the bed. I found them in the same positions. Jake at the counter, Luna watching. This time, I stayed hidden in the doorway. Jake was crushing something with the back of a spoon. Grape powder, into a glass. He filled it with water from the tap and stirred. Then he opened the fridge and pulled out the pitcher of filtered water I drank from every morning. The pitcher I always refilled before bed. He poured the powder mixture into my water pitcher. My blood went cold. I crept back upstairs, mind racing. Luna followed silently. I've been feeling sick for months. Dizzy spells, nausea, constant fatigue. My doctor ran tests but found nothing wrong. Probably stress, she'd said. Maybe depression. Jake had been so caring, bringing me breakfast in bed when I felt too weak to get up, making sure I stayed hydrated. Drink your water, babe. You need fluids. The next morning, I pretended to drink from the pitcher, but poured it down the sink when he wasn't looking. By afternoon, I felt better than I had in weeks. That night, I set my phone to record and hit it on the kitchen counter. At 2:47, Luna and I crept downstairs. Same scene. Jake crushing pills, mixing powder, contaminating my water. This time, I could see the pill bottle. Ambien. My prescription sleep aids that I'd stopped taking months ago because they made me too groggy. But the Bottle was still full. I checked last week. He'd been refilling it, getting extra pills somehow. Crushing them into my water. Every night while I slept. I watched him pour the mixture into my pitcher, then add something else. A small. A vial of clear liquid. My hands shook as I filmed Luna pressed against my leg, solid and warm. Jake sealed the vial and tucked it behind the coffee maker. Then he rinsed the glass and spoon, wiping everything clean. After, he went upstairs. Retrieve the vial. No label. I photographed everything and took the vial to hide in my car. The next day, I called my doctor. I need a blood test. Test for everything. She found traces of zolpidem and ethylene glycol in my system. Sleeping pills and antifreeze. This is attempted murder, she said quietly. We need to call the police. I'd been slowly dying for months. Symptoms? Dizziness, nausea, confusion, or textbook antifreeze poisoning. Jake had been increasing the dose gradually, making it look like a mysterious illness. The life insurance policy he'd convinced me to increase six months ago suddenly made sense. Police arrested Jake that evening. They found more vials hidden in his toolbox in the garage. Enough antifreeze to kill me three times over. In his phone, they discovered internet searches. How long does antifreeze poisoning take? Undetectable poisons, life insurance waiting periods. He'd been planning this for over a year. Luna had known something was wrong long before I did. Dogs, Can smell chemical changes in their owners. She'd been trying to protect me the only way she knew how. By making sure I was awake when he was poisoning me.

What's the most savage insult you've ever heard from a child? My six year old nephew absolutely destroyed my sister at Thanksgiving dinner. And honestly, she deserved it. My sister Emma has always been obsessed with appearances. Perfect makeup, designer clothes, constantly taking selfies. She's the type who spends two hours getting ready just to go to target. At family dinners, she'd always make these passive aggressive comments about everyone else's life choices. So we're all sitting around the table last Thanksgiving, Emma shows up an hour late because she had to get her nails done. She's wearing this ridiculous white dress to a family dinner where we're eating gravy and cranberry sauce. Classic Emma move. She immediately starts her usual routine. Comments about how mom's stuffing has too much salt this year. Mentions how Uncle Rick should probably lay off the dinner rolls. Makes this big show of only eating tiny portions because she's watching her figure. Then she turns to my brother Jake, who just started community college. Jake, still taking those little classes? When are you going to get a real degree? Jake just stared at his plate. The kids working two jobs to pay for school. Emma kept going. She asked my cousin about her starter apartment and wondered when she'd get a grown up job. She even made a comment about Dad's old truck in the driveway, saying it was embarrassing. The whole time, my nephew Tyler was just sitting there eating his Turkey and Watching Tyler's Jake's six year old son. Super quiet kid, usually just plays with his food and doesn't say much during adult conversations. Emma was on a roll. She started talking about her new boyfriend's BMW and how they're looking at condos downtown. Really laying it on thick about how successful she is compared to everyone else. Then she made her biggest mistake. She looked at Tyler and said, Tyler, sweetie, make sure you study hard in school so you don't end up like your daddy, okay? The table went dead silent. Jake's face turned red. Mom literally gasped. Dad put down his fork and just stared at Emma. But Tyler. Tyler just looked up from his mashed potatoes, blinked those big innocent eyes, and said in the sweetest voice ever, Aunt Emma, why?

The most inaccurate thing your child has ever been taught in school. My daughter's fourth grade teacher told her class that blood is blue inside your body and only turns red when it hits oxygen. Lily came home repeating this fact while showing me her veins. I gently explained, that's actually not true. Blood is always red because of hemoglobin, just darker red in veins. She looked at me confused, but Missus Wilson showed us a whole Powerpoint about it. Dad. She even had diagrams from a science book. Next morning, I packed my work scrubs in my bag. I'm an ER nurse at Mercy General and I was working the 3 p m. Shift. Anyway, I sent Missus Wilson an email asking if I could do a quick 15 minute presentation about blood for Career Day that afternoon. She loved the idea. When I arrived, Missus Wilson introduced me as Lily's dad, who works at the hospital. Twenty eight kids stared up at me from their desks covered in Lisa Frank folders and Minecraft pencil cases. I heard you guys Learned that blood is blue inside your body, I said. The entire class nodded enthusiastically. Missus Wilson beamed from her desk. I pulled out a vacutainer blood collection tube from my pocket. This is what we use to draw blood at the hospital. Notice something? I held it up. The tube creates a vacuum. No oxygen inside at all. Missus Wilson smile started fading as I explained. When we Draw blood with these. It never touches oxygen until we pop the cap off. But I showed photos on my phone of sealed blood tubes. See? Still red. The kids were fascinated. I showed them medical textbook pages on my tablet. Missus Wilson kept clearing her throat, her face getting redder than the blood samples on my screen. But our textbook says it's blue, one boy argued, pointing to their science book. I walked over and checked the publication date. 1998. Medicine updates pretty fast, I explained. We used to think lots of things that turned out to be wrong. Missus Wilson suddenly stood up. Well, thank you for that interesting presentation, Mister. Johnson, but we need to move on to math now. I nodded and started packing up when a girl raised her hand. So our textbook is wrong? The class erupted in whispers. Mrs. Wilson's voice got tight. The curriculum says. Actually, I interrupted, up the state science standards on my phone. The current curriculum specifically mentions this myth as something to correct. I showed her the screen. That's when she asked me to step into the hallway. The kids watched wide eyed as the door closed behind us. Do you have any idea how hard it is to teach these kids when parents undermine my authority? She hissed. Now they'll question everything I say. I kept my voice calm. Isn't that exactly what we want them to do? You question things and learn critical thinking? I've been Teaching for 22 years, she snapped. I'm not changing my whole curriculum because some nurse thinks he knows better than our textbooks. That night, Lily asked me if she was in trouble because Missus Wilson kept giving her mean looks all afternoon. I assured her she wasn't. The next day, Missus Wilson announced a pop quiz with questions like what colour is blood inside the body? Lily answered red and got marked wrong. She came home crying with a big red F. I requested a meeting with the principal and brought printouts of medical textbooks, state science standards, and Lily's quiz. Principal Davis, listen carefully, then called in Missus Wilson. When confronted with the evidence, Missus Wilson insisted, this is how I've always taught it. Principal Davis asked, but is it correct? After a long pause, Missus Wilson said, it's what the children understand better. I lost it. My daughter is crying every morning before school because she's afraid of getting F's for writing down the Truth. Two weeks later, the school replaced their 1998 science books. Missus Wilson was required to attend professional development on current scientific standards. On Lily's next report card, Missus Wilson wrote, excellent critical thinking skills. But at the parent teacher conference, she wouldn't look me in the eye. And when I signed up to help with the science fair, I noticed my name had been crossed off the volunteer list. Lily still checks with me whenever she learns something new at school. Dad is This actually true or is it just a Missus Wilson truth?

Flight attendants, what's the most entitled behaviour you've seen from a passenger? I worked as a flight attendant for eight years, and nothing tops the day I met Princess Pamela, who thought buying a first class ticket meant she owned the entire plane. It started when she boarded wearing a tiara. Yes, an actual tiara, and demanded that everyone call her princess. Not even kidding. She had this designer handbag that probably cost more than my monthly salary, and she kept waving it around like a royal scepter. As I helped store her carry on, she looked me dead in the eyes and said, I expect to be served my champagne exactly three minutes after take off. Not two minutes, not four minutes, three. And it better be at precisely 41 degrees Fahrenheit. She then pulled out a digital thermometer from her purse and placed it on her armrest. Before take off, she complained about the peasants in economy class being able to see her through the curtain. We actually tried to convince my colleague Ben to build a proper wall between the cabins using blankets and pillows. The real show started when we hit turbulence. Thirty minutes into the flight, Princess Pamela started pressing her call button like she was playing whack a mole at Chuck E. Cheese. When I reached her seat, she demanded we turn off the turbulence because it was ruining her blowout. I tried explaining that turbulence wasn't something we could troll. She scoffed, and Said, well, I paid $3,000 for this ticket. I'm pretty sure that covers the cost of smooth air. Then she pulled out her phone and threatened to call her daddy, who apparently owns half of Manhattan. The situation escalated when another first class passenger, this sweet elderly man named Howard, started laughing at her antics. Princess Pamela whipped around and hissed, how dare you mock me? Do you know who I am? Howard, bless his heart, just smiled and said, yes, you're the grown woman wearing a tiara from Claire's. The entire first class cabin erupted in Snickers. That's when she lost it. She stood up during the turbulence, despite the seatbelt sign being on, raised her champagne glass, and announced she was going to have every single person on the plane fired, including the pilot. Then Karma hit. Quite literally. A strong bout of turbulence sent her designer bag flying, spilling its contents everywhere. Her authentic designer wallet split open, revealing dozens of maxed out credit cards and overdue Bill notices. Tiara fell off, too. And guess what? Howard was right. It still had the Claire's price tag stuck to the bottom, 1299. The best part? One of the other passengers recognized her. Turned out Princess Pamela worked at a nail salon in New Jersey. The daddy who owned half of Manhattan was actually her second cousin, who managed a hot dog stand near Times Square. She spent the rest of the flight hiding under her blanket. But we could Still hear her fake crying and mumbling about how she was going to sue everyone on this aircraft. When we landed, she tried to be the first one off the plane, but Howard stood up and blocked the aisle with his cane. After you, Princess, he said, gesturing to all the economy passengers. She had to walk through the entire plane while everyone who'd heard about her meltdown stared and whispered the cherry on top at baggage claim. Her carefully curated facade completely crumbled when her knockoff designer suitcase broke open, spilling Claire's tiaras everywhere. Apparently, she'd been reselling them online as authentic royal headpieces.

Twenty. Eight year old woman. And when I was 13, my parents left me at a gas station to teach me a lesson. They never imagined I'd take that lesson seriously. It happened during one of those long, sticky summer road trips. The van was packed. Two siblings, a cooler full of melting sandwiches, my dad's country music playing just a little too loud. We were somewhere in the middle of nowhere. A stretch of cracked road framed by flat fields and heat shimmer. I asked for water, and my mom told me to run inside and grab a bottle. I hopped out, jogged into the gas station, found a cold bottle from the fridge, and walked to the counter with a couple of crumpled bills. I remember thinking I'd beat my siblings back to the van. I actually smiled. But when I stepped outside, the van was gone. At first I waited on the curb. Five minutes and 10. I walked around the side of the building, thinking maybe they pulled up to the air pump or went around the back. Nothing. I checked inside again. Still nothing. The cashier asked if I was okay. I told him my parents were probably just messing with me. I waited 30 minutes on that metal bench outside the door. Then an hour. The sun moved, shadows shifted, and the cars that came and went were never the right one. Cashier let me use the phone behind the counter. I dialed home. No answer. I tried my mom's cell, then my dad's. I left a voicemail. Another hour passed. The cashier called the local pool police. When the officers showed up, I gave them everything I could remember. Full names, our street address, what the van looked like, what everyone was wearing. One of the officers stayed with me while the other made a few calls. They offered me a juice from the mini fridge while I waited. Six hours after I'd been left there, my parents pulled back into the lot. No speeding, no panic. They parked like they were stopping for fuel. My mother stepped out first, adjusted her sunglasses, and asked the officers what the big deal was. She told them it was discipline, that I'd been acting out, and they thought I needed a wake up call. A reminder of what happens when you're careless or forget to follow directions. My father just nodded along, arms crossed. The police didn't press charges. They said it was a parental overreaction, but that no law had technically been broken. They warned my parents not to do anything like that again. I sat in the backseat of the van the whole drive home, silent. No one said anything to me. My brother laughed the next morning and said I looked like a scared puppy. When they finally picked me up, my sister rolled her eyes and told me to stop being dramatic. At school that fall, I didn't tell anyone what Happened. I just became quiet, focused. I turned in my assignments early, stayed out of group activities, ate lunch alone when I could. I stopped expecting birthday cakes or bedtime hugs. I stopped expecting anything, really. I started preparing quietly. I kept granola bars in my backpack, just in case. Learned how to open my bedroom window from the outside using a fork. I began hiding emergency cash in an old DVD case. I didn't know what I was preparing for. I just knew I needed to be ready for the next time I was left behind. We never spoke about the gas station again. Not even once. It became one of those family moments that got edited out like a bad photo. Everyone moved on except me. I never really had a choice. When I turned 18, I applied to every out of State College I could afford the application fee for. I got into one six states away. I packed everything I owned into two suitcases and left the morning after graduation. No party, no photos. No one helped me load the cab. My mother was watering her plants when I left. My father didn't look up from the television. I moved into a dorm with strangers and never went back. Over the years, I built something for myself. It wasn't perfect, but it was mine. A job I earned without any referrals. An apartment I furnished, one thrifted chair at a time. Friends who hugged hello and remembered My birthday. People who noticed when I was quiet and asked if I was okay. No one ever left me standing alone in a parking lot. I didn't cut my parents off completely. I didn't block their numbers. I didn't change mine. But I never called. I never messaged first. The last time I saw them was three years ago at a cousin's wedding. They smiled like everything was normal. Like I hadn't spent hours alone at 13. Wondering if I'd been kidnapped or forgotten. And now, 15 years later, something's happened. Something big. Something that dragged them back into my life. After all this time, they're about to learn what it really feels like to be left behind for good. Last week, I got a call from my mother. It came through in the middle of a work day. I saw

Poor people who have dated rich people. What did you learn? When I started dating William, I didn't know his family owned half the expensive restaurants in our city. I was a waitress at a diner, making minimum wage, living in a tiny studio apartment with a broken heater. On our first date, I suggested we meet at my usual coffee spot. He showed up in a Tesla, looking completely out of place among the regular customers with their chipped mugs and laptop chargers. I noticed right away how he kept touching everything with his sleeve pulled over his hand. When I asked if he wanted to split a muffin, he politely declined, saying he wasn't hungry. Later, I found out he'd never eaten at a place that didn't have at least one Michelin star. Despite our differences, we clicked. He was funny, smart, and genuinely interested in my life. He didn't act superior when I told him about my community college classes or my dreams of opening my own bakery someday. everything changed when he invited me to his family's monthly dinner. I spent two weeks tips on a dress from a consignment shop. It was navy blue with tiny pearls on the collar, the nicest thing I'd ever owned. When I arrived at their mansion, the maid who opened the door looked more expensive than me. William's mother took one look at my dress and said, oh, darling, is that vintage? How sustainable of you. The dinner Was a nightmare. They had five different forks, and I used the wrong one for my salad. William's sister asked what my parents did for a living. When I explained that my mom worked at Walmart and my dad wasn't in the picture, she choked on her wine. But where did you summer as a child? He asked, completely serious. Then came the incident that changed everything. William's mother announced that their chef had prepared a special truffle risotto. I took one bite, and my throat started closing up. Turns out they'd use some fancy mushroom I was severely allergic to. Didn't have my Epipen because I'd never encountered it at any place I could actually afford to eat. William rushed me to the hospital in his Tesla. While I was still on the journey, his mother swept in, wearing her designer coat. Instead of asking if I was okay, she pulled William aside, and I heard her whisper, darling, if she can't even handle proper cuisine, how will she survive the Governor's Ball? That's when William surprised everyone. He turned to his mother and said, actually, Nancy makes the best chocolate souffle I've ever tasted. Better than your chefs. Mother gasped like he'd slapped her. She's been teaching me to bake, he continued. I'm investing in her bakery idea. And if you can't handle that, we won't be at any of your balls. His mother stormed out. Later that night, still in my hospital gown, William confessed something he'd Been taking secret baking lessons at a community center. Because he wanted to understand my passion. He showed me videos on his phone. Him covered in flour, burning cookies, setting off smoke alarms. Three years later, our bakery, Humble Crumbs, is the most popular spot in town. We serve both two dollar cookies and two hundred dollar wedding cakes. William's mother still won't eat here, but his sister became our biggest customer. She even admitted our five dollar muffins taste better than the fifty dollar ones at her country club. The best part? We still use those chipped mugs from our first date coffee shop. I bought their whole set when they were going out of business. William doesn't use his sleeve to touch them anymore. Last week, a food critic called our place unpretentiously perfect. William framed the review right next to my old consignment shop dress.

What was a loophole that you found and exploded the hell out of? My university had this stupid rule where we couldn't have pets in our dorms, not even fish. The punishment was a 500 dollar fine and immediate removal of the animal. But my therapy cat, Luna, helped with my anxiety attacks. I wasn't about to give her up. Barbara, our dorm supervisor, was absolutely obsessed with enforcing this rule. She done random room checks for 15 years and bragged about confiscating over 50 pets. She even kept a wall of photos in her office showing all the contraband animals she'd caught, like some twisted trophy collection. My first week, she caught someone with a hamster and made this huge show of calling animal control. While the poor girl sobbed, Barbara just stood there smirking, telling everyone, rules are rules, dear. I knew I had to be smart about keeping Luna, so instead of just sneaking her in, I spent three days reading every single page of the university's housing policies. Most of it was boring stuff about noise levels and trash disposal. But on page 43, I found exactly what I needed. No pets or animals are permitted in university housing facilities unless specifically required for documented medical conditions. The keyword was documented. Nowhere did it specify who needed to do the documenting. So I went to my regular therapist and got her to write an official letter stating that Luna was essential for managing my anxiety. I Also printed out research papers about the benefits of emotional support animals. When Barbara burst into my room during a random inspection and saw Luna, her eyes lit up like she just won the lottery. Well, well, what do we have here?

video_description: What happens if a chain smoker quits smoking suddenly#ask #askreddit #LearnOnTikTok #reddit #story #satisfying #relaxing
voice_to_text: What happens if a chain smoker quit smoking? Suddenly, day one without cigarettes and my body declared war on me. I've been smoking since I was 15. Half my life spent inhaling roughly 14,600 packs. That 292,000 cigarettes. At five minutes per cigarette, I'd spent nearly three years of my life just smoking. The decision wasn't dramatic. No cancer diagnosis or ultimatum. Just a moment when I watched my five year old daughter pretend to smoke a crayon, holding it exactly how I hold my marl bros. Right down to the way she flicked imaginary ash. What are you doing, Emma? I asked, already knowing I'm being you, daddy, she said, taking another pretend drag. I quit that night. Flushed the cigarettes, deleted my smoke break alarms and told no one. Previous attempts had failed when announced, like my brain needed an audience for its surrender. By 10:00am Wednesday, my hands trembled so badly I spilled coffee across my keyboard. My coworker noticed. Hangover? He asked. Quitting smoking, I admitted. His eyebrows shot up. Cold Turkey. Jesus, Mark, that's like jumping out of a plane without checking if your parachute works. By afternoon, the headache arrived. Not dull, but primal, like my skull was being crushed in a vice. Every sound became weaponized. The office printer might as well have been a jackhammer beside my ear. That night, I dreamt of cigarettes. Not just smoking them, I was swimming through to them. Thousands floating in a sea of tobacco. Each One calling my name. Day two brought rage, pure, irrational fury that made me snap at Emma for dropping her spoon at breakfast. It's just a spoon, I shouted immediately, horrified at myself. Her little face crumpled. My wife Jen took her to school instead of me. Get it together, she whispered. Call your doctor. My doctor prescribed nicotine patches, which felt like cheating, but also like survival. Your brain is literally rewiring itself, he explained. The receptors that have been flooded with nicotine for years are screaming for it. Day three. The insomnia was so bad I hallucinated. My mouth produced saliva like I was about to vomit. Constantly. Food tasted like wet cardboard. I found myself standing outside a gas station at 2 a m. Staring at the cigarette ads. Making a teenager exiting looked at me with concern. You okay, Mister? I wasn't, but I didn't buy cigarettes. Day 5 brought the dreams again. I dreamt I was smoking and woke up with crushing guilt, patting the bed for cigarette burns before realizing it wasn't real. The physical symptoms were brutal, but nothing compared to the psychological warfare. Every stress trigger felt like neon signs flashing S M O K E N O W. Day 7. Could suddenly smell everything. My co workers Cologne from across the room, the garbage from inside the house while I was still in the driveway. The lingering smoke in my car upholstery that I've been nose blind to for years. I Deep cleaned my car that weekend, gagging at the yellow residue that came off the windows. Day 14. I could climb the stairs without sounding like I was dying. My daughter noticed. Daddy, you're not making the scary breathing anymore. Day 30. The craving still ambushed me, but less frequently. I gained 8 pounds, but my skin had lost its grayish tint. My wife kissed me one morning and paused. Your mouth tastes friend, she said. Better. Day 60. I found an old jacket with a forgotten pack in the pocket. Instead of excitement, I felt revulsion. I showed my wife, who watched nervously as I crushed each one under the faucet. I didn't think you'd actually do it this time, she admitted. Neither did I, I confessed. It's been six months now. The money I've saved, nearly $2,000, paid for Emma's first real bicycle and a weekend away with my wife. My persistent cough disappeared. Food tastes incredible. Sometimes I still reach for cigarettes that aren't there. Phantom limb syndrome, but for addiction. But when Emma hugged me yesterday and said, you smell nice, daddy, instead of wrinkling her nose and pulling away, I knew with absolute certainty I would never smoke again. The war isn't over, but for the first time, I'm winning.

What's the moment that made you decide being nice wasn't working anymore? I used to be the person everyone called when they needed something. The one who would drop everything to help a friend move or stay late at work to finish someone else's project. My boss would text me at 11 p m. And I'd respond immediately. I'd cover shifts when co workers called in sick. I'd volunteer for the projects nobody wanted. I was raised to believe kindness would always come back to you. For five years at Davidson Media, I was the first to arrive and last to leave. I helped my co workers meet their deadlines. I brought coffee for the team when everyone was stressed. I even let my boss, Diane, take credit for my ideas during presentations because she said it would look better coming from management. When my dad got sick last year, I asked Diane if I could work remotely two days a week so I could drive him to chemo. She sighed and said, we really need you in the office, but I suppose we can make it work for a month or two. I was so grateful that I worked twice as hard on my office days, making sure nothing fell through the cracks. Dad's treatment was supposed to last six months, but after three months, Diane called me into her office. She said the remote arrangement wasn't working. The team needed me physically present every day. And besides, it Had been long enough. I explained that dad was only halfway through treatment. He couldn't drive himself and had no one else. She just stared at me until I lowered my eyes and said, I understand. I spent the next week burning through my savings to hire drivers for dad. I was exhausted, constantly worried about him, but still the first one in the office every morning. Then came the Maxwell Project, a huge account that could make or break our quarter. I spent weeks researching, building the pitch, creating mockups, everything. I even missed one of Dad's appointments to finish it. The day before the presentation, Diane asked to see my materials. I handed over everything, including my presentation notes. The next morning, I arrived early, excited to present my work, only to find the conference room already full. Diane was at the head of the table, showing my slides to the clients. I stood in the doorway, frozen as she used my exact words. My research, my ideas. When she saw me, she smiled and said, oh, good. Jennifer, can you grab coffee for everyone? We're just getting started. The client turned, saw me, and said, aren't you presenting this? Before I could answer, Diane jumped in and said, oh, no, this is my project. Jennifer just helped with some research. I got the coffee. I stood in the back of the room and watched as she was praised for my work. The client loved it. They signed A three year contract, the biggest in company history. When the executives came down to congratulate the team, Diane accepted all the praise. She got a bonus, she got a promotion. I got a fifty dollar gift card to Starbucks. That night, dad called. He'd fallen trying to get from the taxi to his front door. He had been lying on the ground for 20 minutes before a neighbor found him. If I had been there. I kept thinking, if I had just been there. Two days later, the company held a Celebration for the Maxwell deal. Diane was given an award. I stood and clapped with everyone else. Then came the announcement that made everything stop. Diane would now head up a new division created specifically for the Maxwell account. And she needed a strong team. She spent 10 minutes talking about the qualities she was looking for, then announced her first hire. Ryan. The guy who had been with the company for six months and hadn't contributed a single thing to the project. I sat there stunned as everyone congratulated him. Then Diane looked at me and said, Jennifer, I need those quarterly reports by end of day. I know you won't let me down. Something broke inside me. Five years. Five years of saying yes, of staying late, of missing time with my sick father. Five years of watching others take credit for my work. Five years of being nice. I stood up, walked to the bathroom, And stared at myself in the mirror. My hands were shaking. I barely recognized the woman looking back at me. That was the moment, that exact moment, when I decided being nice wasn't working anymore. I couldn't fit. What happens next in this short video. Watch the rest down below.

They gave me the worst room on the family trip. They didn't know I own the hotel. I decided to keep quiet and observe the annual family reunion. It was a tradition my mother insisted on maintaining, though for me it always meant a weekend of constant comparisons and cutting remarks. This year would be no different, except that the luxurious hotel where we would stay was now my property, thanks to the inheritance my grandfather had secretly left me six months earlier. When I arrived at the lobby of Hotel Miramar, my heart was beating fast. I watched as my sister Lucia, the family favorite, was welcomed with hugs and smiles by everyone. No one noticed my presence until my mother saw me and frowned. I thought you wouldn't come, Carmen, she said, not bothering to hide her disappointment. I wouldn't miss our family reunion for anything in the world, I replied with a smile that didn't reach my eyes. My brother in law, Roberto, Luccia's husband, looked me up and down, evaluating my outfit as always. Seems like the graphic design business isn't so lucrative after all, he commented with a mocking smile. If only they knew my small company was now a respected agency with international clients. But I never bothered to correct their assumptions. What hurt me most was the secret I kept. This five star hotel with its impeccable gardens and Ocean View now belonged to me. Grandfather had always seen something in me that the Rest of the family ignored. We distributed the rooms, my mother announced as manager. Miguel handed out the keys. My sister and her husband received the presidential suite with Ocean View. My parents an executive suite, my cousins deluxe rooms. And me. Carmen, you'll stay in room 1 0 8 on the first floor, the room next to the laundry. The smallest and noisiest room in the hotel. Everyone exchanged glances, some with shame, others with poorly disguised amusement. Miguel, the manager, seemed uncomfortable. Ma'am, we could look for another option for the young lady, he began, but my mother interrupted him. It's not necessary. Carmen is simple. She doesn't need luxuries. I saw how Miguel looked at me with concern. He knew who I really was. But we had agreed to keep my position as owner's secret during this family reunion. It's fine, Miguel, I said calmly. Room 1:08 will be perfect. I took the key and headed to the elevator, feeling my family's eyes on my back. On the way, I heard my cousin Daniela whisper, as always, Carmen settles for the leftovers. The room was exactly as I remembered, small, with a window overlooking the service area and the constant noise of the laundry machines. I sat on a single bed and took a deep breath. I wasn't here to confront my family or to humiliate them by revealing I was the owner. I was here to understand why they treated me this way. Why, after 30 years, They still saw me as the least valuable. That night, during the welcome dinner at the hotel restaurant, my family occupied the best table. My chair was partially hidden behind a column. While everyone ordered the most expensive dishes on the menu, I ordered a simple salad. Can't you afford something better, Carmen? My father asked with a mixture of mockery and pity. We can treat you if you want. The salad is fine, thank you, I replied, maintaining my dignity. The conversation revolved, as always, around Lucia's achievements, her recent promotion at the bank, her new house in the exclusive neighborhood. Our Lucia always knew what she wanted, my mother said proudly. Not like Carmen, who wasted her life with his drawing business. The head chef approached our table to personally greet the guests. Upon seeing me, he made a small bow that didn't go unnoticed. Was the salad to your liking, Miss Carmen? He asked respectfully. Delicious, Antonio. Thank you, I replied. My family looked at me strangely. You know the chef? Lucia asked, surprised. We've crossed paths before, I replied vaguely. The truth was that I had personally hired Antonio three months earlier, after grandfather left me the hotel. The night progressed, and with each glass of wine, the comments directed at me became more cutting. The secret I kept was weighing on me more and more. Should I reveal the truth? What would they do if they knew that every insult, every humiliation occurred under my Own roof, Miguel approached discreetly. Miss Carmen, there's an urgent matter that requires your attention, he said quietly. If you don't want to wait for part 2, you can watch the full story on my YouTube channel. Just click on share and then more, and then click on the YouTube link here in my profile. Or search for the Flag Stories Reddit channel on YouTube.
