Fathers. What did your daughter's boyfriend do that forever changed how you saw him as a cop? I hated the idea of my 17 year old daughter dating anyone. But when she brought home this boy named Pete, I lost it. He had a motorcycle, tattoos, and that smug smile that made me want to run his name through the system. I made it my mission to break them up. I'd randomly show up at places they hung out, flash my badge around, and remind Pete that I knew how to make bodies disappear. But this kid never flinched. He just smile and say, have a good day, sir. When he came for dinner the first time, I placed my gun on the table next to my plate. My wife kicked me under the table, but I didn't care. Pete just looked at it and said, nice Glock 19, sir. My uncle's got the same one at his security firm. That's when the real torture began. I started making him come over every weekend to bond. I'd have him help me with the most backbreaking chores I could think of. Reshingling the roof in July, digging out a tree stump by hand, moving every piece of furniture in the house to steam clean the carpets. This kid never complained. He'd show up at 7:00am sharp, already wearing work clothes. Even brought his own work gloves. When I try to wear him down with endless tasks, he just say, what's next, Sir, one Saturday, I had him helping me rebuild the deck. I was being extra harsh, making him redo boards that were perfectly fine. Around noon, my daughter brought us water. As she walked away, I caught Pete watching her. But it wasn't the way most teenage boys looked at girls. He had this soft smile, like he was watching something precious. I decided to test him. You know she's way out of your league, right? He wiped his forehead and said, oh, I know, sir. Trust me. I know. That's why I'm here every weekend, letting you test me. Because she's worth it. When did you realize your parents were bad at parenting? When I was 11, my mom would drop me off at the local mall every weekend with $15 and her credit card for emergencies only. She called it our arrangement. She got me time and I got independence training. The first few Saturdays, I thought I was the luckiest kid alive. Freedom, a food court and the arcade. I'd stretch that $15 by getting the free pizza samples and spending hours at GameStop. This college age employee, Marcus, noticed me hanging around every weekend. Back again, buddy, he'd say. Then let me play the display consoles longer than other kids. By my fourth solo Saturday, I had a routine. I knew which restaurants gave the biggest samples, which bathrooms were cleanest, and where to sit to charge my phone. I'd text mom updates like she asked, but she rarely responded until pickup time. This older security guard, Officer Ray, started appearing wherever I went. One rainy Saturday, when the mall was nearly empty, he sat down across from me in the food court. Your mom works nearby? He asked casually. I nodded, repeating the line she taught me. She's at important meetings. I'm old enough to handle myself. He studied me for a moment, then slid me his half finished pretzel. My shift ends in an hour. I can never finish these. What started as occasional Saturdays became every weekend, then extended to Friday nights, too. Mom would text last Minute. Can you handle dinner at the mall? Use the emergency card. Love you. I'd watch movies alone, sitting between families so I wouldn't look weird. Once, a dad offered me some of their popcorn, thinking I'd been separated from my parents. The kindness made my throat tight. The worst day was when I got food poisoning from day old sushi. He helped me clean up and took me to the security office, where they called my mom 17 times. No answer. They finally reached her four hours later. He was at a spa retreat three hours away. Can he just take an Uber home? She asked them. The mall manager had seen me alone too many times. He showed Officer Ray footage of me wandering alone from opening till closing, Friday nights through Sunday evenings for six straight weekends. I remember Officer Ray's face hardening as he watched. When my mom finally arrived the next morning, she brought me a milkshake like everything was fine. The security office had called child services. Mom kept saying he's mature for his age and kids need independence these days. The case worker just kept writing in her note. The funniest way you've proved a teacher wrong. I recently turned in my English essay, and the next day, my teacher called me up to her desk. I was feeling pretty good. I actually put effort into this one. Maybe she was going to compliment my writing. Nope. She folded her hands, looked at me like a detective about to crack a case, and said, there's no way you wrote this. I laughed, thinking she was joking. She wasn't. She picked up my paper and pointed at a word. Ubiquitous. I nodded, yeah. She narrowed her eyes. You don't even know what that means. Now I knew this wasn't about my essay anymore. This was personal. I calmly defined the word, used it in three different sentences, and even threw in a synonym for extra credit. She crossed her arms. Okay, you must have used AI to write this. What? First I was too dumb to know big words. Now I was too smart to have written this myself. She made me run my essay through an AI detector. It came back 100% human written. At this point, I had proved her wrong twice, but she still would not back down. She tapped her desk, pretending to think, then went, then you must have copied this from another essay. I couldn't believe it. I literally wrote this from scratch, but now I was being accused of plagiarism. I told her to run it through a plagiarism checker. I did, and I passed. I sat back, arms crossed. Now, surely she'd apologize. She sighed, looked me in the eyes, and handed me my paper with a big fat zero written at the top. I stared at it. Wait, so what's the reason now? She shrugged. I just don't believe you. At that point, I was done. I stood up, walked to the door, and before I left I turned around, looked her dead in the eyes, and said, you know what's really ubiquitous? Your terrible grading. Then I walked out with my zero and my dignity.
